<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
T-Bill Rates Higher at Auction: The Treasury sold $8.6 billion of new 
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.73%, up from 7.69% last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
Another $8.6 billion of new six-month bills was sold at an average discount 
rate of 7.64%, up from 7.62% the week before. The new discount rates understate 
the actual return to investors: 7.99% for three-month bills, with a $10,000 
bill selling for $9,804.60, and 8.06% for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,613.80. The discount rate reflects the discount received when government 
securities are purchased at less than face value. In a separate report, the 
Federal Reserve reported that the average yield for one-year T-bills fell to 
8.08% last week from 8.18%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Chart, T-Bill Auction 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
