<HEADLINE>
<P>
KURDS LAUNCH BIGGEST RAID IN TURKEY SINCE '88 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANKARA, Turkey 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rebel Kurds launched their most deadly attack in two years Sunday night, 
killing at least 20 civilians in a remote village in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
The Anatolian News Agency said Monday that at least 20 civilians were killed, 
and sources in the regional city of Diyarbakir said the toll could reach 26. 
</P>
<P>
The raid on Cevrimli village, 30 miles north of the Iraqi and Syrian borders, 
showed that the Marxist Kurdish Workers Party is still a potent force despite 
renewed government efforts to stamp out a six-year insurgency. It was the 
rebels' biggest operation since 25 villagers were killed in nearby Mardin 
province in May, 1988. 
</P>
