<DATELINE>
<P>
KATMANDU, Nepal 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nepal, the world's only Hindu kingdom, will free all Christian prisoners who 
were jailed by the former government for illegal proselytizing, the royal 
palace said today. 
</P>
<P>
The palace said in a statement King Birendra has "granted amnesty to all 
religious prisoners" on the advice of Prime Minister Krishna Prasad Bhattarai 
in view of the "new political environment . . . in the country." 
</P>
<P>
Currently, 29 Christians, including 14 children younger than age 18, are 
serving sentences for proselytizing. There are no religious prisoners of other 
faiths. A human rights report recently said 144 other Christians are in police 
custody across the country facing trial. 
