<P>
STEVE HOWE HOSPITALIZED WITH BLOOD CLOT ON LUNG; 
</P>
<P>
BASEBALL: ILLNESS INTERRUPTS COMEBACK WITH CLASS A SALINAS SPURS OF THE 
CALIFORNIA LEAGUE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LANCASTER 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former Dodgers relief ace Steve Howe, in the middle of another baseball 
comeback, has been hospitalized with a blood clot in his lung. 
</P>
<P>
Howe's condition was upgraded to satisfactory and he was transferred from the 
critical care unit to the regular nursing area Monday afternoon, said Frankie 
Edwards, director of public relations at Antelope Valley Hospital Medical 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
June Snow, administrative assistant at the hospital, said after Howe was 
hospitalized that he was receiving an anticoagulant in an attempt to dissolve 
the clot. 
</P>
<P>
Howe was pitching for the Salinas Spurs of the Class A California League. Howe, 
0-1, hadn't allowed an earned run in nine innings while striking out 10 and 
walking two. 
</P>
<P>
"Everything depends on if the anticoagulant works," Salinas General Manager 
John Jonas told the Antelope Valley Press. "Surgery may be required if it 
doesn't." 
</P>
<P>
If surgery is required, Howe's career "may be on the line," Jonas said. 
</P>
<P>
Howe, 32, was taken to the hospital Saturday afternoon and admitted in serious 
condition. He was in Antelope Valley to speak to junior high students about the 
dangers of drug use. 
</P>
<P>
Howe, the National League rookie of the year in 1980, faced a series of 
suspensions for cocaine use, the first in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
Doctors have refused to comment if Howe's current ailment had any connection 
with his previous drug use. 
</P>
<P>
Howe was released by the Dodgers in 1985. In 1986, Howe attempted a comeback 
with the San Jose Bees of the California League, and then signed with the Texas 
Rangers. Texas paid a $250,000 penalty in order to promote Howe to its 
major-league roster in spite of Howe's lifetime ban. 
</P>
<P>
Howe later violated his Texas contract on a non-drug-related matter and was 
released. 
</P>
<P>
Howe published his autobiography, "Between the Lines," in 1989. He has been an 
active speaker on the dangers of drug use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
